00:19:29,543 --> 00:19:32,671
It shows in your face
that you know I'm your mother.

238
00:19:32,713 --> 00:19:35,299
-What about your husband?
-Oh, I don't have one.

239
00:19:35,341 --> 00:19:37,259
What about you -
ever been married?

240
00:19:37,301 --> 00:19:38,636
-Yes.
-How's that going?

241
00:19:38,677 --> 00:19:41,889
-Y'know, there's a certain presumption...
-Don't lock Bernice out.

242
00:19:41,931 --> 00:19:44,600
-She loved the people who raised her.
-You're her mother.

243
00:19:44,642 --> 00:19:47,645
-But it's natural she would have questions.
-I'm sitting here!

244
00:19:53,859 --> 00:19:55,319
Yes, you are.

245
00:19:55,361 --> 00:19:56,737
Ask me anything.

246
00:19:57,738 --> 00:20:01,951
You're sitting on anger. Ask me anything,
hit hard, ask me anything you want.

247
00:20:01,992 --> 00:20:04,620
Why did you give me up?

248
00:20:08,290 --> 00:20:11,544
"On you will go,
though the weather be foul.

249
00:20:11,585 --> 00:20:14,422
"On you will go,
though your enemies prowl.

250
00:20:14,463 --> 00:20:16,674
"Onward up many a frightening creek

251
00:20:16,715 --> 00:20:20,469
"Though your arms may get sore
and your sneakers may leak. "

252
00:20:21,846 --> 00:20:25,099
-What?
-It's a book, by Dr. Seuss.

253
00:20:25,141 --> 00:20:27,351
-Did your adoptive parents read it to you?
-No.

254
00:20:27,393 --> 00:20:31,147
Oh, that's a shame,
because it's a map of your life really.

255
00:20:31,188 --> 00:20:34,817
The whole point of which
is that every ending is a beginning.

256
00:20:34,859 --> 00:20:38,237
Now, when Trudy and Julius passed,
that was an ending,

257
00:20:38,279 --> 00:20:43,743
but in a funny kind of a silver liningy way,
it's brought us together, hasn't it?

258
00:20:44,660 --> 00:20:45,995
I have to go.

259
00:20:46,704 --> 00:20:48,205
Wait. Stop.

260
00:20:48,247 --> 00:20:50,708
Don't... Don't go.

261
00:20:50,750 --> 00:20:53,627
-Gabrielle!
-April, goddammit!

262
00:20:56,297 --> 00:20:59,633
Would you like to know
who your father was?

263
00:20:59,675 --> 00:21:01,677
He was a famous man, now dead.

264
00:21:05,431 --> 00:21:07,308
Why don't we go to my office
and really talk?

265
00:21:07,349 --> 00:21:09,435
-Thank you, no.
-We could go for a drive.

266
00:21:09,477 --> 00:21:11,729
-I would like to walk.
-Oh, you like to walk?

267
00:21:11,771 --> 00:21:13,105
You sound like your father.

268
00:21:13,147 --> 00:21:15,399
My famous father, now dead,
went for walks?

269
00:21:15,441 --> 00:21:19,820
I'm a walker myself, you know.
All kinds of exercise, I'm a nut for.

270
00:21:19,820 --> 00:21:21,697
Could we slow down for just a moment?

271
00:21:22,865 --> 00:21:26,452
Oh, being related like this
is just incredible.

272
00:21:26,494 --> 00:21:28,454
You were saying about my father?

273
00:21:28,496 --> 00:21:29,914
You hardly know me yet.

274
00:21:29,955 --> 00:21:32,458
Well, thank you, Ms. Graves,

275
00:21:32,500 --> 00:21:35,878
it was traumatic and
potentially illuminating to have met you.

276
00:21:37,588 --> 00:21:39,465
I met him when I was fifteen.

277
00:21:39,507 --> 00:21:41,926
-I worked in perfume.
-Where, exactly?

278
00:21:41,967 --> 00:21:44,220
Well, four blocks that way,
as it happens.

279
00:21:44,261 --> 00:21:46,722
Used to be Bonwit Teller.
You can look it up.

280
00:21:46,764 --> 00:21:50,351
Since I wasn't rich, I earned extra money
working in their perfume department.

281
00:21:50,392 --> 00:21:53,729
-So this was a customer?
-Oh, a very special customer.

282
00:21:53,771 --> 00:21:57,650
He came in to buy a gift for his mother.
He was close to his mother, too close,

283
00:21:57,691 --> 00:22:00,069
-because no woman could measure up.
-Who was it?

284
00:22:00,111 --> 00:22:03,072
He was immediately flirtatious,
but not in a boorish way.

285
00:22:03,114 --> 00:22:07,493
He was, and I say this in all humility...
enchanted.

286
00:22:07,535 --> 00:22:09,995
-Who was it?
-Steve McQueen.

287
00:22:11,664 --> 00:22:14,250
-How dare you.
-We were deeply in love.

288
00:22:14,291 --> 00:22:15,668
Well, what went wrong?

289
00:22:15,709 --> 00:22:17,795
He was single when I met him.
Separated, anyway.

290
00:22:17,837 --> 00:22:21,006
I never would've gotten involved
had his relationship been viable,

291
00:22:21,048 --> 00:22:23,175
but I sensed they weren't through.

292
00:22:23,217 --> 00:22:25,678
"They" would be Steve McQueen
and Ali MacGraw?

293
00:22:25,719 --> 00:22:30,266
If you watch The Getaway, you'll sense
a certain closeness. I feel good about that.

294
00:22:30,307 --> 00:22:32,518
By the way, do you have any children?

295
00:22:32,560 --> 00:22:35,646
-Was it a one-night stand?
-Oh, the memory lasted a lifetime.

296
00:22:37,064 --> 00:22:39,024
Your generation is so cynical.

297
00:22:39,066 --> 00:22:41,402
-When was I conceived?
-Around the fourth of July.

298
00:22:41,444 --> 00:22:42,611
-Around or on?
-On!

299
00:22:42,653 --> 00:22:45,322
-Was he right or left handed?
-What kind of question is that?

300
00:22:45,364 --> 00:22:46,365
Circumcised?

301
00:22:46,407 --> 00:22:48,659
Catholic.
I understand your parents were Jewish.

302
00:22:48,701 --> 00:22:50,244
-So what? So am I.
-Well, God bless.

303
00:22:50,286 --> 00:22:52,830
-What does that mean?
-God bless that you believe in God.

304
00:22:52,872 --> 00:22:57,001
-You don't believe in God?
-I don't know. Watched the news lately?

305
00:22:57,042 --> 00:23:00,588
I'll ask you one more time,
why did you give me up?

306
00:23:00,629 --> 00:23:03,090
I didn't give you up.
You were taken from me.

307
00:23:04,383 --> 00:23:05,801
Didn't they tell you that?

308
00:23:07,219 --> 00:23:09,680
My father was very religious.

309
00:23:09,722 --> 00:23:13,726
I held you in my arms for three days,
praying that it wouldn't happen.

310
00:23:13,768 --> 00:23:15,102
But it did.

311
00:23:15,144 --> 00:23:18,856
He walked in, he took you,
and he left me screaming.

312
00:23:18,898 --> 00:23:21,150
How do I know any of this is true?

313
00:23:21,192 --> 00:23:23,110
Because it is!

314
00:23:24,487 --> 00:23:29,617
All right, listen to me,
and please respect what I say to you.

315
00:23:29,658 --> 00:23:35,206
I have to go home, think about this,
and decide what to believe.

316
00:23:35,247 --> 00:23:36,749
OK.

317
00:23:37,583 --> 00:23:39,085
OK.

318
00:23:40,503 --> 00:23:41,837
Thank you.

319
00:23:43,923 --> 00:23:46,175
-I appreciate you...
-Can you drop me?

320
00:23:47,760 --> 00:23:49,220
What? Where?

321
00:23:49,261 --> 00:23:50,930
Back there.

322
00:23:50,971 --> 00:23:52,681
All right.

323
00:24:07,071 --> 00:24:08,697
When can we do this again?

324
00:24:10,991 --> 00:24:13,119
Everyone needs family.

325
00:24:16,997 --> 00:24:19,041
I will call you.

326
00:24:19,083 --> 00:24:21,293
Let me give you my number.
Do you have a pen?

327
00:24:25,131 --> 00:24:26,632
OK.

328
00:24:27,007 --> 00:24:28,300
Give me your hand.

329
00:24:29,385 --> 00:24:30,886
Please?

330
00:24:40,312 --> 00:24:42,022
It's harder to lose a hand.

331
00:24:53,451 --> 00:24:56,245
<i>This isn't just
a thousand-to-one shot.</i>

332
00:24:56,287 --> 00:24:59,290
<i>This is a professional blood sport.</i>

333
00:24:59,331 --> 00:25:01,167
<i>It can happen to you.</i>

334
00:25:02,168 --> 00:25:04,044
<i>And then it can happen to you again.</i>

335
00:25:07,423 --> 00:25:09,133
I want my mommy!

336
00:25:09,175 --> 00:25:12,052
Hi, everybody.
Thanks for your patience.

337
00:25:12,052 --> 00:25:16,599
-Oh, some more than others.
-I want my mommy! I want my mommy!

338
00:25:16,640 --> 00:25:18,809
Ruby, I need you to come here now.
Get your shoes on.

339
00:25:18,851 --> 00:25:22,229
Why don't you come in first?
I mean, for obvious reasons.

340
00:25:22,229 --> 00:25:25,191
That's OK. You go ahead.
Besides, we're having so much fun here.

341
00:25:25,232 --> 00:25:27,359
-Are you sure?
-Of nothing.

342
00:25:27,401 --> 00:25:29,945
I want my mommy!

343
00:25:44,251 --> 00:25:45,878
-Pardon me.
-What!

344
00:25:45,920 --> 00:25:47,713
We're all right. We're fine.

345
00:25:47,755 --> 00:25:51,717
-You're fine? She's fine?
-Yeah, we're fine. Mm-hm, fine.

346
00:25:57,765 --> 00:26:00,851
-Listen, I'm sorry about what I...
-Shh.

347
00:26:03,104 --> 00:26:04,939
I'm sorry about what I said to you.

348
00:26:04,980 --> 00:26:08,818
Listen, I'm four weeks divorced.
For all I know, I was coming on to you.

349
00:26:10,945 --> 00:26:12,571
Were you coming on to me?

350
00:26:12,613 --> 00:26:14,073
No, I wasn't.

351
00:26:15,282 --> 00:26:16,784
Why I wasn't, I can't imagine.

352
00:26:21,622 --> 00:26:23,958
Um, this is Jimmy Ray's portfolio.

353
00:26:23,999 --> 00:26:26,752
-I think he's in trouble.
-You do?

354
00:26:28,129 --> 00:26:30,798
-Sorry, what were you about to say?
-His printing is good.

355
00:26:30,840 --> 00:26:32,091
-Really?
-Mm-hm.

356
00:26:32,133 --> 00:26:34,593
K's made him nervous,
but he likes them now.

357
00:26:34,635 --> 00:26:36,762
-He seems happiest...
-He has night terrors.

358
00:26:36,804 --> 00:26:39,932
-Did you say night terrors?
-I think they're night terrors.

359
00:26:39,974 --> 00:26:42,601
-He walks in his sleep.
-How often?

360
00:26:42,643 --> 00:26:44,770
Once, ten months ago.

361
00:26:44,812 --> 00:26:47,398
-What happened?
-He peed in the fridge.

362
00:26:47,440 --> 00:26:48,899
Have you slept?

363
00:26:48,983 --> 00:26:51,777
Oh, no. No.

364
00:26:55,239 --> 00:26:56,574
I love his hands.

365
00:26:57,908 --> 00:27:03,330
I do. I love how he uses them,
how expressive he is.

366
00:27:03,330 --> 00:27:04,707
I love that, too.

367
00:27:04,749 --> 00:27:07,460
He has a little less confidence
just right at the moment,

368
00:27:07,501 --> 00:27:10,129
-but I think that's to be expected.
-Do you have kids?

369
00:27:12,047 --> 00:27:13,382
No.

370
00:27:15,009 --> 00:27:17,970
He talks about his mom a lot.
He seems to worship her.

371
00:27:18,012 --> 00:27:20,556
From afar.
She's on a trip round the world.

372
00:27:20,598 --> 00:27:23,350
She's a painter. She's painting the world
with her boyfriend.

373
00:27:23,392 --> 00:27:24,727
Oh.

374
00:27:27,146 --> 00:27:29,774
I see you outside in your car. Is that...

375
00:27:29,815 --> 00:27:32,318
Yes. I work out there. I write.

376
00:27:32,359 --> 00:27:33,527
In your car?

377
00:27:33,569 --> 00:27:35,780
I like to keep an eye on the building.
It relaxes me.

378
00:27:35,821 --> 00:27:37,573
Mm.

379
00:27:37,615 --> 00:27:39,450
So why didn't you have kids?

380
00:27:40,326 --> 00:27:42,661
I've watched you. You love them.
And you're...

381
00:27:42,703 --> 00:27:44,080
Old?

382
00:27:44,121 --> 00:27:45,456
No.

383
00:27:46,415 --> 00:27:49,668
No, my God, no. You can't be
more than what, you're 35, 34?

384
00:27:49,710 --> 00:27:52,505
I'm 39 and a half years old
and I've never been pregnant.

385
00:27:52,546 --> 00:27:54,048
Well, if you put it like that.

386
00:27:54,090 --> 00:27:58,010
-It looks pretty bleak, doesn't it?
-No. No, it looks painful.

387
00:28:01,180 --> 00:28:02,848
And beautiful.

388
00:28:03,724 --> 00:28:05,851
And I hope you get everything you want.

389
00:28:12,316 --> 00:28:13,901
Um, dinner.

390
00:28:14,944 --> 00:28:16,612
Apparently I want dinner.

391
00:28:20,699 --> 00:28:23,494
-Well, bon appétit.
-Oh, would you like to get some dinner?

392
00:28:23,536 --> 00:28:26,497
No, I'd rather eat frozen food alone
for the fifteenth month in a row.

393
00:28:26,539 --> 00:28:27,915
Yes, I'd like to get dinner.

394
00:28:27,957 --> 00:28:31,001
But I think
you are a very beautiful woman

395
00:28:31,043 --> 00:28:35,923
and for some reason I decided not to go
on any kind of date for at least a year.

396
00:28:35,965 --> 00:28:38,551
Why? Because I'm a fucking idiot.

397
00:28:38,592 --> 00:28:41,720
Thank you, you're gorgeous.
I'm leaving now.

398
00:28:50,604 --> 00:28:52,231
Yes, I would like to get some dinner.

399
00:28:55,276 --> 00:28:58,028
-Best friends? He said that?
-Mm-hm.

400
00:28:58,070 --> 00:29:00,072
Is this man entirely intact?

401
00:29:00,114 --> 00:29:03,534
You know, we were best friends.
I loved him.

402
00:29:03,576 --> 00:29:06,746
Kept hoping one day, pop,
he'd be a grown-up.

403
00:29:07,788 --> 00:29:09,623
So your wife was seeing someone else?

404
00:29:09,665 --> 00:29:11,375
Pretty much everyone else.

405
00:29:11,417 --> 00:29:13,127
I was too much for her.

406
00:29:13,169 --> 00:29:14,837
-For your wife?
-Mm-hm.

407
00:29:14,879 --> 00:29:16,547
I'm sure she didn't feel that way.

408
00:29:16,589 --> 00:29:18,257
-She told me.
-What did she say?

409
00:29:18,299 --> 00:29:20,050
"You're too much for me. "

410
00:29:20,092 --> 00:29:22,970
Ohh! So was it just out of the blue?

411
00:29:24,180 --> 00:29:26,974
It was out of the blue
because I was an idiot.

412
00:29:27,016 --> 00:29:29,769
I came across the ocean
to be a blind idiot.

413
00:29:30,978 --> 00:29:34,815
This woman may actually let her kids
grow up without knowing their mother.

414
00:29:34,857 --> 00:29:36,400
I hope not.

415
00:29:37,985 --> 00:29:39,987
How can you know
if someone's your mother?

416
00:29:40,988 --> 00:29:45,743
I mean, literally, if someone says they're
your mother, how can you know for sure?

417
00:29:45,785 --> 00:29:47,453
DNA test, I guess. Why?

418
00:30:01,759 --> 00:30:04,053
I mean, you don't not look like
Steve McQueen.

419
00:30:05,638 --> 00:30:07,973
-Is she a credible person?
-I have no idea.

420
00:30:10,518 --> 00:30:13,521
My God, you have a chance
to get to know your mother.

421
00:30:15,606 --> 00:30:17,149
Yes, I guess I do.

422
00:30:19,360 --> 00:30:21,362
What do you write in here?

423
00:30:21,403 --> 00:30:22,863
Books.

424
00:30:23,864 --> 00:30:28,828
Jackets. Jackets for other people's books.
For now.

425
00:30:42,716 --> 00:30:44,927
-Get a hair.
-I'm sorry?

426
00:30:44,969 --> 00:30:47,179
For the DNA test. Get a hair.

427
00:30:47,221 --> 00:30:48,597
Oh.

428
00:30:49,807 --> 00:30:51,142
Thank you.

429
00:30:54,395 --> 00:30:55,771
Well.

430
00:30:57,648 --> 00:31:00,234
-I don't wanna say good night.
-I don't either.

431
00:31:01,277 --> 00:31:02,736
Uh-oh.

432
00:31:04,864 --> 00:31:08,075
You suppose my son would notice if I just
didn't pick him up from his play day?

433
00:31:08,117 --> 00:31:09,869
I'm sure he'd understand.

434
00:31:14,874 --> 00:31:16,709
OK, I need you to do something for me.

435
00:31:16,751 --> 00:31:18,711
I need you to get in your car.
Which is your car?

436
00:31:19,545 --> 00:31:23,132
Yeah, I need you to get in your car
and drive away, first. Because I can't.

437
00:31:23,174 --> 00:31:24,717
Will you do that for me?

438
00:31:24,759 --> 00:31:26,218
-Seriously?
-Yes.

439
00:31:28,929 --> 00:31:30,389
You will go home, right?

440
00:31:30,431 --> 00:31:33,851
I won't find you guys here in the morning
wearing the same thing?

441
00:31:36,020 --> 00:31:40,065
-OK. Good night.
-Good night.

442
00:31:43,527 --> 00:31:46,906
Maybe I should call you when you
get home, just so you can be sure.

443
00:31:49,116 --> 00:31:53,037
I'd appreciate that. I worry.

444
00:31:53,079 --> 00:31:54,497
Yeah, I do, too.

445
00:31:57,541 --> 00:31:59,126
What are you making?

446
00:31:59,168 --> 00:32:01,754
Well, it's peanut butter and jelly.
And I have to confess

447
00:32:01,796 --> 00:32:04,548
that we don't share your countrymen's love
of peanut butter.

448
00:32:06,092 --> 00:32:10,221
And jelly isn't jelly. That's another thing
I have to have a word with you about.

449
00:32:11,305 --> 00:32:14,266
Well, if you were in England,
what would you be making?

450
00:32:14,308 --> 00:32:16,727
This would probably be
cheese and pickle.

451
00:32:16,769 --> 00:32:18,896
Did you say cheese and pickle?

452
00:32:18,938 --> 00:32:20,272
You don't know what pickle is.

453
00:32:20,272 --> 00:32:22,566
You give me a hard time
about peanut butter and jelly

454
00:32:22,608 --> 00:32:23,901
and you say cheese and pickle?

455
00:32:23,943 --> 00:32:28,739
I'm defending food to an Englishman.
Is that happening to me right now?

456
00:32:28,781 --> 00:32:33,035
Our sex life was dominated
by her artwork, you know?

457
00:32:33,077 --> 00:32:34,495
What do you mean?

458
00:32:34,537 --> 00:32:37,581
Well, she liked to depict acts
of autoeroticism.

459
00:32:37,623 --> 00:32:39,458
Oh.

460
00:32:39,500 --> 00:32:46,590
I sometimes make toast and have tea
after I've brushed my teeth,

461
00:32:46,632 --> 00:32:49,969
and I don't brush them again.
Do you ever do that?

462
00:32:50,010 --> 00:32:54,807
No, no, no, I can't.
I'm, um, I'm British.

463
00:32:54,849 --> 00:32:57,601
<i>#... beautiful girl and I want you to know it #</i>

464
00:33:02,648 --> 00:33:04,775
I was never happier to get a call.

465
00:33:04,817 --> 00:33:08,529
-Hello.
-Hello. Have you eaten yet?

466
00:33:08,571 --> 00:33:11,490
-Um, actually, no.
-Oh, come with me!

467
00:33:12,241 --> 00:33:15,244
Our show went well today,
despite our best efforts,

468
00:33:15,286 --> 00:33:17,538
so, everyone's in a good mood, OK?
AJ?

469
00:33:17,580 --> 00:33:19,373
-Welcome to the craziness.
-Hello.

470
00:33:19,415 --> 00:33:21,000
-Lunch?
-Please. We're famished.

471
00:33:21,041 --> 00:33:22,626
-Sam's?
-Perfect!

472
00:33:22,668 --> 00:33:25,045
What do you feel like?
It's a kind of a pubby place.

473
00:33:25,087 --> 00:33:27,339
Would a hamburger be all right?

474
00:33:27,339 --> 00:33:29,300
-Oh, my God!
-What?

475
00:33:29,341 --> 00:33:32,303
